        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight mb-3 mt-8">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
        <div class="flex flex-col gap-4 mb-8"><div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg p-4"><h3 class="text-sm font-bold mb-2">How often do fire extinguishers need to be inspected in San Jose, CA?</h3><p class="text-sm text-gray-600">Monthly visual inspections by building staff, annual professional inspections by a licensed technician, 6-year internal examinations, and 12-year hydrostatic testing per NFPA 10 and the California Fire Code (Title 19 CCR).</p></div><div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg p-4"><h3 class="text-sm font-bold mb-2">How much does a fire extinguisher inspection cost in San Jose, CA?</h3><p class="text-sm text-gray-600">Annual inspections in the San Jose / Silicon Valley typically cost $20–$50 per unit. 6-year internal examinations run $30–$65. 12-year hydrostatic tests cost $38–$82. Volume discounts apply for 20+ units.</p></div><div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg p-4"><h3 class="text-sm font-bold mb-2">Who can inspect fire extinguishers in San Jose, CA?</h3><p class="text-sm text-gray-600">Monthly visual checks by trained staff. Annual, 6-year, and 12-year service by a licensed technician. California requires fire extinguisher service contractors to hold an OSFM license. Verify at osfm.fire.ca.gov before scheduling service. The Santa Clara County Fire Department serves unincorporated county areas — the San Jose Fire Department is the AHJ for buildings within city limits.</p></div><div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg p-4"><h3 class="text-sm font-bold mb-2">What are the most common fire extinguisher violations in San Jose?</h3><p class="text-sm text-gray-600">The most common violations cited by the San Jose Fire Department include: Missing Class C (CO2) extinguishers in data center and server room environments — standard ABC dry chemical damages electronic equipment; Missing Class K coverage in Japantown and Little Saigon restaurant commercial kitchens.</p></div><div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg p-4"><h3 class="text-sm font-bold mb-2">Does San Jose require fire extinguishers in all commercial buildings?</h3><p class="text-sm text-gray-600">Yes. The California Fire Code (Title 19 CCR) requires portable fire extinguishers in all commercial, industrial, and multi-family residential buildings. Type, size, and placement depend on occupancy classification and hazard level per NFPA 10.</p></div></div>
